SIMPLE: turn-out
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turn-out
<hw>Turn"-out`</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucir⟧rn"out`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Turn-outs</plw> <pr>(t⟦ucir⟧rn"outs`)</pr>.</plu>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of coming forth; a leaving of houses, shops,
etc.; esp., a quitting of employment for the purpose of forcing increase
of wages; a strike; -- opposed to <xex>lockout</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A short side track on a railroad, which may be
occupied by one train while another is passing on a main track; a shunt;
a siding; a switch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is prominently brought forward or
exhibited; hence, an equipage; <as>as, a man with a showy carriage and
horses is said to have a fine <ex>turn-out</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The aggregate number of persons who have come out,
as from their houses, for a special purpose; the number in attendance at
a gathering; <as>as, a light <ex>turnout</ex> for the
election</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Net quantity of produce yielded.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A space alongside a highway where vehicles may stop,
esp. for emergency purposes, or to admire the view.</def> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turnover</ent>⟦br⟧
